{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"72271edb-ea6a-4581-896f-b6c06364a19f","content":"For a .NET Web API project, use the `webapi` template:\n\n```bash\ndotnet new webapi -n MyApi\n```\n\n**Authentication options** (`--auth`):\n\n| Option | Description |\n|--------|-------------|\n| `None` | No authentication (default) |\n| `IndividualB2C` | Azure AD B2C |\n| `SingleOrg` | Single tenant Azure AD |\n| `MultiOrg` | Multi-tenant Azure AD |\n| `Windows` | Windows authentication |\n\n**Example with auth:**\n```bash\ndotnet new webapi --auth SingleOrg --domain yourdomain.onmicrosoft.com\n```\n\nYou can also add JWT Bearer auth manually via `Microsoft.AspNetCore.Authentication.JwtBearer` if you need custom token validation (e.g., Auth0, IdentityServer).\n\nWant me to scaffold a project with a specific auth option?","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"1afe9315-23b3-4d8f-8a2c-2af4b80850f8","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about web API project templates and authentication options. This is a general knowledge question about .NET (likely, given the repository context with dotnet plugins). I can answer this from my knowledge without needing to look at files.\n\nLet me provide a concise answer about dotnet web API templates and authentication options.","outputTokens":291,"requestId":"93EA:1ED665:A45E78:BDC815:69F2A7AF"},"id":"ce427712-e7a9-45fa-98f8-0a399170e1bb","timestamp":"2026-04-30T00:52:06.163Z","parentId":"2bff3c7a-fdbe-42ed-992c-3509c5effae7"}
